<subSubSection id="C36665161756AB67FCB261E99C551C21" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="642" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1756AB60FCB261E99B5A1953" blockId="19.[806,1421,1419,1594]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FCB261E99B041ACA" box="[806,1295,1419,1440]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">
Original diagnosis (
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B6C1756AB60FBB261E99B0B1ACA" author="Daams R" box="[1062,1280,1419,1440]" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" pagination="13 - 26" refId="ref16583" refString="Daams R. 1989. Miscellaneous Gliridae from the Miocene of the Calatayud-Teruel basin, Aragon, Spain. Scripta Geologica 89: 13 - 26." type="journal article" year="1989">Daams, 1989: 16</bibRefCitation>
):
</emphasis>
‘A small 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FCB261C89A3A1AAA" box="[806,1073,1450,1472]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Pseudodryomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FCB261C89DDD1AD5" box="[806,982,1450,1471]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Pseudodryomys</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
with a flat to slightly convex occlusal surface. The M1,2 have a subquadrate circumference. Simple dental pattern. Centrolophs are absent, and centrolophids are short or absent. Protoloph and metaloph form a Y – pattern in M1,2’.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1756AB67FCB262069CD71EF9" blockId="19.[806,1422,1636,1903]" lastBlockId="20.[164,779,198,403]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="642" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FCB262069A1A1913" box="[806,1041,1636,1657]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Emended diagnosis:</emphasis>
Small 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1756AB60FBE462069B471910" box="[1136,1356,1636,1658]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="641" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1756AB60FBE462069AE51913" box="[1136,1262,1636,1657]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="641">Simplomys</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
with molars that have a flat to slightly convex occlusal surface and simple pattern. Anteroloph and posteroloph are situated slightly below the plane of the trigon (protoloph–metaloph). The protoloph and metaloph form a composite ‘Y’ shape with a bent connection. A line connecting the labial end of the metaloph and the lingual end of the protoloph is aligned at right angles to the anteroposterior axis of the tooth. The occlusal surface of the M1 and M2 has a square outline. In M1 the anteroloph and the anterior valley are straight and parallel to the anterior border of the tooth. In the lower molars, the centrolophid is absent or poorly developed and it does not extend into the central valley. The m3 has the posterior part reduced in size and in most cases the posterior valley is absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3369D1751AB67FF3065DF9FE21D45" blockId="20.[164,779,445,559]" pageId="20" pageNumber="642">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1751AB67FF3065DF9C551EB8" box="[164,606,445,466]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="642">
Differential diagnosis: 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1751AB67FE3C65DF9C551EB8" baseAuthorityName="Daams" baseAuthorityYear="1989" box="[424,606,445,466]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="642" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="julii">Simplomys julii</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1751AB67FD6765DC9F381E9B" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1966" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="642" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplicidens">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1751AB67FD6765DC9F381E9B" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="642">S. simplicidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1751AB67FED465BE9FCB1E9B" baseAuthorityName="De Bruijn" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[320,448,476,497]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="642" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1751AB67FED465BE9FCB1E9B" box="[320,448,476,497]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="642">S. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D1E1751AB67FE6A65BE9C651E9B" box="[510,622,476,497]" class="Mammalia" family="Gliridae" genus="Simplomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="642" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aljaphi">
<emphasis id="B908EA8F1751AB67FE6A65BE9C651E9B" box="[510,622,476,497]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="642">S. aljaphi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its smaller size, less concave cheek teeth, and by having the centrolophid less developed.
</paragraph>
